{
  format: 1
  name: mixed-direction-keys-apply-per-key-direction
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.5", "§B.1"]
  tags: ["ordering"]
  note: '''
    §7.3 / §B.5: "A leading `-` reverses ONE key" — the direction is per-key,
    not per-sort. The §B.5 worked example is exactly this shape:
    `$sort: ["-$until", "price"]` reverses only the first key and keeps the
    second ascending. Sort keys still compare left-to-right (§B.5).

    Attack: a comparator that applies the leading `-` to the WHOLE comparison
    (reversing every key, or negating the final result) instead of to just the
    first key. `$sort: ["-score", "name"]` means score DESCENDING, then, among
    rows tied on score, name ASCENDING.

    Rows:
      c: score 9, name "Max"
      a: score 5, name "Zoe"
      b: score 5, name "Ana"
      d: score 1, name "Bob"
    Score descending groups the rows 9 > 5 > 1. Within the score-5 tie, name
    ascending orders "Ana" (b) before "Zoe" (a). Correct order: c, b, a, d.
    A whole-comparison reversal would order the score-5 tie by name DESCENDING
    ("Zoe" before "Ana") and emit c, a, b, d — the exact bug this isolates.
    Seed order is scrambled relative to the output.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.mixeddir@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      rows: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        score: "int"
        name: "text"
      }
      $public: {
        ranked: { $view: ".rows { id, score, name, $sort: [-score, name] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      rows: {
        a: { score: 5, name: "Zoe" }
        c: { score: 9, name: "Max" }
        d: { score: 1, name: "Bob" }
        b: { score: 5, name: "Ana" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.ranked", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "c", score: 9, name: "Max" }
        { id: "b", score: 5, name: "Ana" }
        { id: "a", score: 5, name: "Zoe" }
        { id: "d", score: 1, name: "Bob" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
